text:
as we begin planning for 2019, it's important to reflect on what made 2018 such a special year. 2018 is being referred to as "year of the woman" due to the strides women have made throughout the country. at ywca, we had a lot of work to make this happen here at home in union county. 
as the #metoo movement was gaining traction nationally and internationally, we had our 5th annual dv symposium at kean university to lead an open discussion about consent. a month before the historic midterm elections, we celebrated women's leadership by honoring female elected officials throughout union county and the state of new jersey at our 40th anniversary gala. but women's leadership is not exclusive to government. at our 39th annual tribute to women in industry, we honored working women in various fields. 
thank you to all who helped make 2018 such a memorable year. while there were plenty of reasons to celebrate, there is still much work to do in 2019 and years to come to further our mission of eliminating racism and empowering women.
name: YWCA Union County

text: have you seen #survivingrkelly? if you are involved in or been following the #metoo movement it is your duty to watch this, share it, and/or speak out about it. this movement was originally created by #taranaburke in response to the violence againast young black girls which this film explicitly outlines. i couldnâ€™t sleep last night after watching this, thinking of all of the young black girls lives who were ruined and the ways in which we have all been complicit. years ago i began to boycott anything to do with r. kelly, and today i pledge to follow the lead of black women organizers and activists working on this issue and to speak out. please do not look away because you feel this isnâ€™t your issue, or you canâ€™t relate, or you donâ€™t want to be triggered or your a white person and feel uncomfortable. this is an issue we must unite and organize around to show our black and brown sisters that their lives matter. you can watch the series on lifetime or buy it as i did on amazon. take the time to watch it and discuss it, these lives matter and need our support! and if watching this would be too triggering there are other ways to take action. share it, call mca, or volunteer at a hotline. p.s. if this is the first time you are hearing about this series, please take that as an indication that part of the work that needs to be done is to diversify your circle of friends and community. everyone in the black community is talking about this. you should have seen this by now. and if you havenâ€™t then that speaks for itself. everyone in the world heard about the kavanaugh hearings, but black women and girls lives doesnâ€™t get the same attention. letâ€™s do our part to make a change today. you can watch it here: https://www.mylifetime.com/shows/surviving-r-kelly

text:
on day 10 of 25 days of january, i want to talk about body image.

because here's the truth:

complaining about your body won't make you healthier, skinnier, happier or help you love your body.

dissing your body actually makes it even harder to look after yourself properly.

weighing yourself doesn't make you healthier 
it makes you more obsessed with your weight and disordered around food.

loving your body or getting into healthy habits takes time

just like learning a new language or instrument. 
if youâ€™ve been dieting your whole life, your journey will be up and down. 
and that's totally okay. ðŸ˜Š

my advice?

fake it until you make it!

tell yourself how much you love you the bits of your body and why.

thank them for being part of you

and slowly you'll start having more days of appreciation and fewer days of complaining.

text_retweet:
the following is from @placentamagic - savanah kennedy. i encourage you all to share your stories, your trauma. get it out. purge it. burn it. and never return to the same system that abused you...
.
reposted from @placentamagic - â€œhow do you feel your birth went?â€
â €
one of the many student midwives whoâ€™d practiced cervical checks on me sat stiffly next to me on the postpartum ward bed. i wanted to spit on her.
â €
â€œit was great.â€ i said coldly, holding my small, 2 day old baby closer.
â €â €
her eyes darted downwards, presumably towards the papers in her hands, but iâ€™d like to think that for a split second she felt some type of guilt or remorse.
â €
â€œso what are you going to do to stop this from ever happening again?â€ she said catching my eyes once more.
â €
thatâ€™s the moment i got it. i understood. the things done to me werenâ€™t necessary or even accidental, they were retaliative. they were retaliative because of the money they lost when i refused unnecessary procedures and testing.
â €
they were retaliative because i didnâ€™t trust them after they misdiagnosed me 3 times, and i told them.
â €

in preparation for the installation at edward hopper house, i received permission to  photograph source material for the paintings in the space where the hoppers lived and worked on washington square north, in greenwich village. itâ€™s a somewhat sentimental or romantic gesture, photographing a contemporary model in the hopper home, with the same light hopper would have painted from, positioning the figure in the same place jo would have posed--- the model role-playing jo, who was role-playing hopperâ€™s â€œwomenâ€â€¦ but in the paintings that came from this process i was hoping to draw out the lost threads of joâ€™s particular history and connect it to contemporary concerns of agency, identity, access and power. in the final installation, joâ€™s influence is blaring from the walls, seeping into the space, while the expressionless figures, lost forever in thought, meditate on what could have been for jo and what could be for them. 
iâ€™ll be giving a talk this weekend at the nyack public library with @etcolleary if youâ€™re interested in hearing more:) special thanks to two talented  @moraviancollege art students! @jillianmcluhan the model who like jo, has a background in theater and was visibly shapeshifting and finding new characters in front of the camera. @erikasalus helped capture the images, bringing her technical prowess to each shot. ðŸ™ðŸ»ðŸ™ðŸ»ðŸ™ðŸ»â¤ï¸â¤ï¸â¤ï¸

text: obediance to norms of family and in saudi in society puts multiple restrictions on womens lives. there are of course families in saudi who do not practice honorculture but the majority does. and it is everything from covering fully, not going outside unless with a family member, not seeing friends, not working... not living... to marriage with a stranger just to get out of the house, starvation, abuse, imprisonment... being put in dar prisons for women for escaping the family or for disobeying. ending up spending your life in prison. all legal for families to practice in saudi according to male guardianship law- because family first and â€family knows bestâ€- even if they restrict your life to a phone, food and water... or much less. thats not life. life is having a choice. #maleguardianshiphell #stopenslavingsaudiwomen #feminism #feminist #metoo #timesup #honorkilling #honor #shraf #honorabuse #womentogether #solidarity #humanrights #women #womensrights

text:
lady gaga and r. kelly have performed together several times since 2013. 
in the past, lady gaga has defended her decision to work with r. kelly by saying that she too has had plenty of false stories written about her during her career. at the time, the pop star was giving kellz the benefit of the doubt. now, with dozens of women accusing him of sexual misconduct, itâ€™s become pretty clear to her that she needed to speak out to protect her own image.

many artists have denounced r. kelly since the lifetime docu-series surviving r. kelly aired over the weekend and finally, lady gaga has issued an apology for her previous collaboration with the singer. in addition to her apology, she vowed to remove their collaboration, â€œdo what u want,â€ from itunes and streaming services. her statement reads: â€œas a victim of sexual assault myself, i made both the song and the video at a dark time in my life, my intention was to create something extremely defiant and provocative because i was angry and still hadnâ€™t processed the trauma that had occurred in my own life. the song is called â€˜do what u want (with my body),â€™ i think itâ€™s clear how explicitly twisted my thinking was at the time.â€ she ends the message by apologizing for not speaking sooner and for her poor judgment. gaga has been vocal about her experiences with sexual assault and she actively works with survivors to share her own story. read her full statement in the full story at www.itskenbarbie.com (or swipe) what do you guys think about gaga removing the song from outlets? #rkelly #robertkelly #survivingrkelly #lifetime #lifetimetv #trappedinthecloset #metoo #muterkelly #ladygaga #gaga #astarisborn #astarisbornmovie #ladygaganews #monsters #littlemonsters #entertainment #entertainmentnews #entertainmentblog #gossip

text:
a recent study has found that sexual harassment and sexual assault are significantly associated with worse health indicators.
ðŸ§¬
full article @
www.clearvuehealth.com/sahealth
ðŸ§¬
sexual harassment is not only harmful mentally, but also may lead to medical consequences as well, particularly high blood pressure.
ðŸ§¬
the cdc continues to find high a high prevalence of sexual assault against both men and women.
ðŸ§¬
researchers from the university of pittsburgh studied a group of 304 middle aged women to see whether sexual harassment and sexual assault were significantly correlated to health indicators and outcomes.
ðŸ§¬
22% of the patients in the study had reported a history of sexual assault.
researchers estimated that these patients had nearly triple the risk of depression compared to women without a history of sexual harassment, and more the double the risk of anxiety and poor sleep. all three effects were highly statistically significant.
ðŸ§¬
this study found that workplace sexual harassment also leads to real health issues.
ðŸ§¬
they found that 19% of the patients reported a history of workplace sexual harassment. these patients had a significantly higher prevalence of sleep issues and high blood pressure.
ðŸ§¬
according to the cdc, approximately 44% of american women have experienced some type of sexual violence. this includes unwanted sexual contact, rape attempts, sexual coercion, and/or penetration.
ðŸ§¬
if further research confirms that sexual assault doubles or triples a person's risk of depression, anxiety, and poor sleep, then it's plausible that a significant portion of the mental health burden we have in our society today can attributed to sexual violence.
ðŸ§¬
a significant number of men also had experienced some type of sexual violence. while the proportion is lower at 25% vs 44% in women, it certainly warrants further study into the effects of #sexualassault in men.
ðŸ§¬

text:
the awesome card i received from old co-workers in the mail yesterday! itâ€™s amazing to me the number of people, (dozens of which i donâ€™t even know) who have reached out to me since coming forward about the abuse i endured and sharing my story. it has shown me a few things but most importantly that my work in helping others is just beginning. there are so many women out there that have endured their own version of what i did, many of whom never have been able to use their voice to fight for themselves and the love and justice they deserve. i have faith that we can change that together. iâ€™ve also realized that there are a few out there that are going to continue to degrade and fight me for finally coming forward. 30+ year old bullies that find it important to tear me down for stripping their friends facade. whatâ€™s even more important than that handful though is all the love, support and encouragement iâ€™ve received from the many handfuls behind and beside me. i will continue to rise.

text: last august i attended the global lean in regional leaders conference in california. i met some amazing women who spoke and encouraged us to continue on our journey for gender equality in the workplace. joanne lipman was one of those dynamic speakers. i immediately knew i had to have her on the show.Â not only is a powerhouse woman but she is also an encourager and an advocate for women in the workplace. her list of accomplishment is a mile long, including the wall street journal, cco of gannett and so much more. she was also the editor in chief of usa today and is now the author of the book, that's what she said: what men need to know (and women need to tell them) about working together. joanne and i talk about those discussions that we all need to be having with the men we work with. conversations that need to take place about the #metoo topic and how we, as women, can move into a better place of equality. it was a great chat filled with lots of great advice and insights from this fabulous leader. joanne and i also talked about her book club, her best business advice from her former boss and we even talked about her favorite seasonal snack! #linktolisteninbio

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
â€œhow do you feel your birth went?â€
â €
one of the many student midwives whoâ€™d practiced cervical checks on me sat stiffly next to me on the postpartum ward bed. i wanted to spit on her.
â €
â€œit was great.â€ i said coldly, holding my small, 2 day old baby closer.
â €â €
her eyes darted downwards, presumably towards the papers in her hands, but iâ€™d like to think that for a split second she felt some type of guilt or remorse.
â €
â€œso what are you going to do to stop this from ever happening again?â€ she said catching my eyes once more.
â €
thatâ€™s the moment i got it. i understood. the things done to me werenâ€™t necessary or even accidental, they were retaliative. they were retaliative because of the money they lost when i refused unnecessary procedures and testing.
â €
they were retaliative because i didnâ€™t trust them after they misdiagnosed me 3 times, and i told them.
â €
why did i tell them?
â €
â€œoh excuse me â€” i mean, what birth control are we setting you up with?â€
â €
the next 30 minutes were spent listening to the girl drone on about her pseudo cycle pills and implants. after her spill i smiled and told her i was good.
â €
then she told me that i would be pregnant again in the next year because ovulating women, â€œget too caught in the moment to remember protectionâ€.
â €
i donâ€™t think iâ€™ll ever forget how absolutely atrocious her presence in that room was.
â €

text: you set the stage for how others treat you. i have a tendency to care too much for others feelings and making sure they are 'okay' before caring about how i feel about a situation.. i will give you the shirt off my back before i would ever ask why you need it.... and then you extend that offer else where, in all directions before looking back at yourself. what i never really realized in life is that more than not, that person will be grateful and thankful... but then you have those others who will suck the life out of you and because you are who you are... you won't realize it until its too late. then you're left wondering wtf you did wrong. don't take this as a don't be kind, be heartless, and cold. what i'm saying is fill your cup first and take no shit! limit yourself to how much you give, know your limits. its okay to cancel plans and to say no. its okay to tell a friend or family member that they're being a dick and you need to breathe for a moment. its okay to take care yourself, fully, before caring about any other! â™¥

text:
in the end of last year i illustrated an article for anmesty international about self-determination. the article was written by marie kajava and you can read it on amnesty finlandâ€™s website.

in the illustrations i highlighted the three main issues surrounding self-determination. 
the right to your gender identity and rightful gender markers and the right to get your desired treatment to fit your transition. stopping forced surgery on intersex children and letting them choose themselves if they wish to have surgery to allign with their gender identity. and the right to choose over your body, who touches it, when and how. 
it was an honor to illustrate this article on this very important topic.

text:

_____
"if i am someone who believes there is going to be retaliation, or the person who committed and perpetrated the events against me is well-respected, has a high-profile within a community, a community i care about, i am going to see a lot of risk related to reporting, particularly because it will instigate an investigation, and that might be a risk i'm not willing to take," - keeli sorensen

in october 2018 i ended a 4 year long abusive relationship. my life changed drastically in a 1000 ways. some negative. some positive. all for a reason. my new years resolution is to talk about it. i have been too scared, embarrassed and forbidden to do that. i want to share my story and hear yours. i want to help others heal while also healing myself. i want to live my life freely. time is precious. donâ€™t waste it with the wrong people.

text:
review:
colette (directed by wash westmoreland, 2018)
all throughout history, women have had to fight hard to have the same recognition as men as intellectually equal human beings capable of revolutionising the world of science, technologies, and humanities. in this beautifully crafted inspiring story, we follow the early life of colette, one of the most prolific french female writers of all time. this isn't a film that breaks any new ground in terms of its storytelling, it's a fairly traditional period biopic, however, it does break new ground in the way it brings such a groundbreaking figure to the big screen and tells us not only an empowering female story, but also an empowering lgbtq story, about a woman who fought and defied all gender norms imposed on her. keira knightley is absolutely incredible as the title character and breaths such depth into this unique historical figure, in this story of a woman who breaks the chains put on her by a male-dominated society that imposes itself on her and who fights against a possessive husband who is more concerned about profiting from her talent and gaining fame than giving her any real freedom or recognition. this film portrays with such compassion the story of this incredible woman who was able to overcome the pressures of patriarchy and establish herself as her own independent individual woman. this is a story that was not only important back then, but it's still very much important in this era of #metoo, where women are still fighting to be recognised as as much capable artists as men. this is a well-crafted, beautifully filmed movie that you should definitely check out.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
after watching the #survivingrkelly documentary, i was horrified and unfortunately not just because of the stories of survivors but also because the unbelievable amount of victim shaming i saw in comments on posts online, accusing these women who were underage children, at the time of the alleged abuse, as "cheque-collecting wanna-be's who knew exactly what they were getting themselves into" and although my message to these trolls may never reach them, today i stand in solidarity to each and every victim of abuse and predators, of any age, worldwide who are suffering in silence or speaking out to end the shame. i also stand in solidarity to @taranajaneen who started the #metoo movement and campaigns and organisations who provide support to survivors... â¤ï¸
â€¢
unfortunately, in the midst of all the disbelief, victim shaming and trolling towards these women, so many supporters of the #muterkelly movement are also being dragged for "jumping on the wagon" or "not giving a fuck sooner" and i just wanna let you know that it's never to late to create and support change! ðŸ’ª
â€¢
i grew up in a strict christian, afro-caribbean household where i wasn't allowed to listen to "pop music" and when @rkelly was initially accused of child pornography, i was too young to know what it was and protected from it and as these allegations have unfolded over the past few years, i didn't have social media or more importantly, the courage to support such movements but now that i have, i refuse to stay silent on shit that matters! ðŸ¤
â€¢
i also raise awareness to sex, love, dating, relationships and shame every single day. i am not jumping on a band wagon. i'm using my wagon to jump up and down about this topic, in defense and support of survivors! ðŸ—£ï¸
â€¢
silence breeds shame... and shame prevents change âŒ
â€¢
we really must get our heads and acts together when it comes to accepting and dealing with these despicable things, because although we may not be able to change the world, we can change our worlds and as a collective, protect as many of our loved ones from falling victim to predators â¤ï¸
â€¢
#endvictimshaming #metoomvmt #whyididntreport

text: â€œtrauma, by definition, is unbearable and intolerable. it produces physiological changes, including a recalibration of the brainâ€™s alarm system, an increase in stress hormones activity , and alterations in the system that filters relevant informations from irrelevant. we now know that trauma compromises the brain area that communicates the physical, embodied feeling of being alive. these changes explain why traumatized individuals become hypervigilant to threat at the expense of spontaneously engaging in their day-to-day lives. they also help us understand why traumatized people so often keep repeating the same problems and have such trouble learning from experience. we now know that their behaviours are not the result of moral failings or signs of lack of willpower or bad characterâ€”they are caused by actual changes in the brain.â€ #thebodykeepsthescore #besselvanderkolk #trauma #treatment

text:
as a mom to a boy, this is a great reminder. "for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
to all the survivors out there- i write this to you,

that you may find peace. 
because i held on too tightly of that pain and rage.

i hope you find strength to truly love yourself.

that you may center yourself and find happiness by fully and truly accepting  who you are- despite what happened.

i hope you can reach a place where you donâ€™t need affirmation from others because you alone- are more than enough.

that you can be bold enough to forgive yourself.

be kind to yourself because you are doing everything that you can.

i hope you can keep moving, listen to your own voice because you have one.

and may your own voice move you to rise and lift off from the floor.

because the beauty of pain and darkness is the perseverance that makes you stronger.

and i tell you this, when you move on and let go.

and you free yourself from all of the rancor,

you will feel the sun again and it feels so damn good. 
because you survived,
because you are loved,
beautiful in all of your ways.

strong with dreams,
driven with goals,
filled with compassion. 
my love to you ðŸ’œâ¤ï¸,
katrina lee .
.
.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

kogan maintains that everything he did was legal and he had a â€œclose working relationshipâ€ with facebook, which had granted him permission for his apps.

cambridge analytica had its data. this was the foundation of everything it did next â€“ how it extracted psychological insights from the â€œseedersâ€ and then built an algorithm to profile millions more.

for more than a year, the reporting around what cambridge analytica did or didnâ€™t do for trump has revolved around the question of â€œpsychographicsâ€, but wylie points out: â€œeverything was built on the back of that data. the models, the algorithm. everything. why wouldnâ€™t you use it in your biggest campaign ever?â€ in december 2015, the guardianâ€™s harry davies published the first report about cambridge analytica acquiring facebook data and using it to support ted cruz in his campaign to be the us republican candidate. but it wasnâ€™t until many months later that facebook took action. and then, all they did was write a letter. in august 2016, shortly before the us election, and two years after the breach took place, facebookâ€™s lawyers wrote to wylie, who left cambridge analytica in 2014, and told him the data had been illicitly obtained and that â€œgsr was not authorised to share or sell itâ€. they said it must be deleted immediately.

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

more than a quaer-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, suppoing him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i am so pleased to have been invited to a meeting with devon and cornwall constabulary to speak with them about survivors experiences of using the police. 
i meet many survivors of domestic and sexual abuse who worry about the response they may get from agencies, especially the police. 
historical abuse where memories are fragmented, buried or hazy pose survivors with all sorts of worries about being believed and a lack of evidence.

i have had two very different experiences with police officers this week when chatting about my abuse.

one was empathetic, warm, professional and listened.

the other was harder, did not listen and made me feel like was wasting police time.
i challenged the attitude of the officer and they admitted that they weren't the 'touchy feely type'. horse's for courses and all that shenanigans, but really?? you come and see a victim of historical abuse and you're not touchy feely!! times need to change!! #underreported #underresourced #police #historicalabuse #trust #listeningskills #warmheart #metoo #sayitloud #campaigning #wontshutup
#speakoutsisterhood #timesup
#woman #mission #brave
name: Danielle Downey

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
punk rock? we need to talk. .
. like most people in the early glam and punk scene, david bowie used his fame , power,  and access to drugs that lower sexual inhibitions to prey on at least one adolescent girl. #iggypop wrote a song about 13 year old sable starr leaving him for #johnnythunders. #jagger , #jimmypage ... it's all of them. sexual predators are the rule in rock and roll, not the exception. .
.
 these men who so define rebellion have never done all that much of it when you really think about it. using drugs, money, and celebrity to have sex with inherently vulnerable people is the status quo.
.
.
i came of age as a female in a punk scene. i was queer and looking for people as weird as i felt. what i found was decent music, a set of ethics that seemed to align with my own thoughts about society, and people angry at things i was angry about. i was also introduced to drugs and sexual violence, two things that went on to define my young adulthood. .
.
in these spaces i frequently interacted with men much older than me who,  looking back, had no business hanging out with adolescents. they werent cool. they weren't punk rock. they were losers who used drugs and street cred as currency for the admiration of children. they were predators. we were children. .
.
if i could define punk as a culture i would call it hypocritical and devoid of the very ethics it subscribes to. it's rebel-adjacent patriarchal bullshit and no place for an actual anarchist . it's a mirage beyond which a lot of irreparable damage has been done at the expense of vulnerable people -- people with 2,000 times more potential for creativity and rebellion than the washed-up drunks and j*nkies, these punx larpers who hold all the laud, the esteem but none of the conviction, none of the heart, with brains long since pickled.
.
.
i guess u could say over the past few years i have pulled away from the scene i once defined myself by, as embarassing as that is to say at 31. honestly, it was never genuine; i was always a million times too real/objectively badass for a scene rife with wet-brained, hedonistic posers lol
.
2 punx 4 punx, i suppose. it's not me -- it's you.
. ðŸ¤˜ðŸ‘‹âœŒ
#oldhead
#recovery

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
diversity and inclusion isnâ€™t just an issue for large-scale corporate organisations or for those who can afford to employ a diversity manager. it is a mindset and underpins the culture of your organisation, no matter the size.
our third top tip to implementing a strategy is:
monitor, monitor, monitor
look around you. does your organisation reflect the world outside and most importantly the world in which your customers live?
organisations that mirror the customers they serve have a greater understanding of their wants and needs and therefore are more efficient and effective in developing successful products and services.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significan notly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

this year toxic chemical has had particular significance as the nerve agent poisoning ( Ð½ÐµÑ€Ð²Ð½Ð¾-Ð¿Ð°Ñ€Ð°Ð»Ð¸Ñ‚Ð¸Ñ‡ÐµÑÐºÐ¸Ð¹ Ð³Ð°Ð·). ongoing international attention to the case, where former russian office and his daughter were attacked, including rising concern over who has access to the worldâ€™s toxic chemical stockpiles, ensured that â€˜chemicalâ€™ topped the list of words most frequently seen alongside toxic in 2018.
.
similarly literal and deadly are toxic substance, toxic gas, and toxic waste, with the latter especially becoming a focal point as the us seeks to combat the spread of toxic waste in the wake of hurricanes and people speak out against businesses burning toxic waste, notably in india.
.
this burning of toxic waste, resulting in the release of toxic gases, has been identified as one of a number of causes of toxic air. air pollution has rapidly become a prime public health concern, and global attention reached a high in october 2018 when the world health organization published its report into the quality of air breathed by children worldwide.
.
the termÂ toxic environment itself, however, has been more frequently used in reference to harmful workplace environment.

text: i have retroactively decided to post one thing a day to my ig page because i would like to be a little better at small consistant habits for appreciating my days. fortunately i only decided to do this a few days late into january. i am not usually a new years resolution type of person, but 2018 was a year of a tremendous changes and i expect 2019 will be in also  change me in ways i haven't even considered yet. so it feels like an appropriate moment to cultivate a small habit.  in the spirit of catch up and also thinking about photos with a lot of story to tell: these headshots were taken by the vancouver tourism board in san jose a few months ago. this year american anthropological association was held in san jose in the middle of the wildfires. it was a deeply intense conference. i spoke on a panel about #metoo in academia & anthropology. preparing to speak about my experiences of sexual assault & harassment on personal, professional, institutional & societal levels was also intense. the night before i presented, i was assaulted by a man who followed me from my hotel to a restaurant pre-mtg dinner. i had to walk into the middle of traffic to safety. friends intervened. police called. i slept poorly but pulled myself together. the evening following my talk, i was aggressively propositioned literally while recounting the events of the previous night to a colleague while waiting for our order in a take out restaurant. i was shaken. i was taken in by a wonderful group of generous, funny new colleagues & friends. we played jenga & gossiped until i could barely stay awake. it was a healing night in the midst of stress, fear & exhaustion. the next morning, these photos were taken. sometimes i see deep sadness in my eyes. sometimes i see the joy of a jenga hangover. often both. i always see my grandmother in the jaunty (too jaunty, let's be real) angle of my hat. these are far from the best or my favorite photos of myself.  but there are stories carved into them. as an anthropologist and a woman, i see a value in that. next week it will be a year since i was violently assaulted in front of my home. i strive to heal myself & others a little more. thanks for being here.

text:
on average, nearly 20 people per minute are physically abused by an intimate partner in the united states. during one year, this equates to more than 10 million women and men.
1 in 4 women and 1 in 9 men experience severe intimate partner physical violence, intimate partner contact sexual violence, and/or intimate partner stalking with impacts such as injury, fearfulness, post-traumatic stress disorder, use of victim services, contraction of sexually transmitted diseases, etc.
1 in 3 women and 1 in 4 men have experienced some form ofÂ physical violence by an intimate partner.Â this includes a range of behaviors (e.g. slapping, shoving, pushing) and in some cases might not be considered "domestic violence." 1 in 7 women and 1 in 25 men have been injured by an intimate partner.
1 in 10 women have been raped by an intimate partner. data is unavailable on male victims.
1 in 4 women and 1 in 7 men have been victims ofÂ severeÂ physical violence (e.g. beating, burning, strangling)Â by an intimate partner in their lifetime.
1 in 7 women and 1 in 18 men have been stalked by an intimate partner during their lifetime to the point in which they felt very fearful or believed that they or someone close to them would be harmed or killed.
on a typical day, there are more than 20,000 phone calls placed to domestic violence hotlines nationwide.
the presence of a gun in a domestic violence situation increases the risk of homicide by 500%.
intimate partner violence accounts for 15% of all violent crime.
women between the ages of 18-24 are most commonly abused by an intimate partner.
19% of domestic violence involves a weapon.
domestic victimization is correlated with a higher rate of depression and suicidal behavior.
only 34% of people who are injured by intimate partners receive medical care for their injuries.

text:
children and domestic violence
1 in 15 children are exposed to intimate partner violence each year, and 90% of these children are eyewitnesses to this violence.
economic impact
victims of intimate partner violence lose a total of 8.0 million days of paid work each year.
the cost of intimate partner violence exceeds $8.3 billion per year.
between 21-60% of victims of intimate partner violence lose their jobs due to reasons stemming from the abuse.
between 2003 and 2008, 142 women were murdered in their workplace by their abuser, 78% of women killed in the workplace during this timeframe.
physical/mental impact
women abused by their intimate partners are more vulnerable to contracting hiv or other stiâ€™s due to forced intercourse or prolonged exposure to stress.
studies suggest that there is a relationship between intimate partner violence and depression and suicidal behavior.
physical, mental, and sexual and reproductive health effects have been linked with intimate partner violence including adolescent pregnancy, unintended pregnancy in general, miscarriage, stillbirth, intrauterineÂ hemorrhage, nutritional deficiency, abdominal pain and other gastrointestinal problems, neurological disorders, chronic pain, disability, anxiety and post-traumatic stress disorder (ptsd), as well as noncommunicable diseases such as hypertension, cancer and cardiovascular diseases. victims of domestic violence are also at higher risk for developing addictions to alcohol, tobacco, or drugs.

text:
rape
1 in 5 women and 1 in 71 men in the united states has been raped in their lifetime.
almost half of female (46.7%) and male (44.9%) victims of rape in the united states were raped by an acquaintance. of these, 45.4% of female rape victims and 29% of male rape victims were raped by an intimate partner.
stalking
19.3 million women and 5.1 million men in the united states have been stalked in their lifetime.Â 60.8% of female stalking victims and 43.5% men reported being stalked by a current or former intimate partner.
homicide
a study of intimate partner homicides found that 20% of victims were not the intimate partners themselves, but family members, friends, neighbors, persons who intervened, law enforcement responders, or bystanders.
72% of all murder-suicides involve an intimate partner; 94% of the victims of these murder suicides are female.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
iâ€™m going to ring in 2019 with a story from last year that made my blood boil. letâ€™s talk about lena dunham - everyoneâ€™s favorite (white) feminist.
.
in 2017, a black woman named aurora perrineau accused a male writer on lena dunhamâ€™s girls, of rape. lena dunham went on to publicly discredit the testimony of the raped woman saying â€œour insider knowledge of murrayâ€™s situation makes us confident that sadly this accusation is one of the 3% of assault cases that are misreported each year.â€
.
basically, dunham claiming a woman lied about being raped. are you still with me? great, hereâ€™s the kicker.

late last year, lena dunham admitted that she had no inside information that supported her claim that perrineau was lying and apologized for discrediting perrineauâ€™s testimony. in other words, dunham lied to protect a man from rape allegations. she went out of her way to discredit another woman.
.
are we outraged yet? because we should be!
.
it is important to address that dunham is white because in this sense, it highlights her privilege. we can argue about this for the next few years, but whiteness is and has always been a privilege. when a white woman speaks, her opinion will automatically be more relevant than a black womans. especially if this woman is a notorious (white) female rights activist. in the black community, itâ€™s well known that dunham has done nothing to support women of color, but in this case sheâ€™s actively trying to discredit the testimony of a black woman in order to protect a white man.
.
itâ€™s also clear that the empathy of dunham hasnâ€™t evolved past her own, privileged mind. she is tone deaf on all social justice issues that arenâ€™t directly about her and she keeps centering herself in matters where her opinions only proves how narcissistic she actually is. and yes, i am well aware that she herself has suffered sexual trauma. it doesnâ€™t excuse her behavior because in having gone through similar experiences she should never discredit another womanâ€™s truth.
.
when you do your best to discredit a voice of the oppressed minorities, you are standing in the way of equality.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
hello all, i feel inclined to share a story of an encounter that i faced earlier in my day to the social media world; so here it is- if youâ€™re living local in las vegas you know that today we had nice weather, as opposed to the past few days, so i decided on my lunch that i would go for a walk. while walking down the street on my lunch in the suburbs a car full of men approached me curb side & yelled â€œiâ€™m 45 & horny!â€ then continued to stare me down as if i was a piece of meat (iâ€™m sure just waiting for a response, which i didnâ€™t give them the time of day) then started laughing & sped off. â€¢

first of all itâ€™s january, iâ€™m wearing a jacket & scarf- how did i even attract your attention? and second, what in your right mind would make you think that is something you can say to or treat anyone?!? if i was older/younger, had an unappealing outwardly appearance or perhaps the complete opposite gender would this have still been said to me? my guess is probably not. â€¢

attention boys- this is not a form of flattery, i donâ€™t feel complimented or flattered. as a woman & survivor i feel completely violated & discomfited. females are not here to serve you as your personal sex object. think of your daughters, sisters & mothers- what if this was something that was said to them & how would it make you feel? â€¢

on the contrary, iâ€™m blessed to have a man in my life that treats me with respect & honors me everyday as the goddess that i am. in america it has been a womanâ€™s right to be free of discrimination & violence since 1923. thatâ€™s 96 years, and is still an ongoing issue in our society. no one should have to feel the need to be on alert for a casual walk down the street.  catcalling is harassment.  #girlpower #womensrights #metoo

hah! just found this true story in my saved posts, as of yet unshared:
.
today i stood down a man with a question mark tattooed between his eyes, who was sexually harassing of one of my employees. indignant, i grew to about ten feet tall on the inside, and calm as basalt i told him off then escorted him out of my rhode island store.
.
he complied of course (who dares take on a giantess?), but on the way out he did tell me to go shoot myself, and yelled â€œyouâ€™re so ugly! so ugly! youâ€™re so ugly you look like a...a...a banana!"
.

text:
"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewwe al of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews
.
.
.

text:
the morals of artists matter

iâ€™ve been part of a recent conversation about picasso that started online, bled into real life and was partly informed by hanna gadsbyâ€™s brilliant picasso takedown in nanette.

iâ€™ve had plenty of time to reflect on picassoâ€™s brutal misogyny and iâ€™ve been plenty repelled by him. for me, seeing the huge retrospective of his work at moma in 1980 was devastating. there was room after room of crying women, women whose lives he ruined with a sense of entitlement that matched his peerless ego.  he bragged about painting what you know, and what man could paint the tears of women better than he? even knowing his sordid biography didnâ€™t give me the breadth of perspective that gadsby developed. her outrage was more articulate than mine, and the subtext, the case that morals matter in the creation and experience of art, belongs within the broader #metoo conversation. 
what surprised me in this conversation that i was part of was how many people, when asked to consider the nature of the man who made the paintings, said theyâ€™d want to hang one in their home. my sister became exasperated with me, saying i made everything political when iâ€™d said nothing about politics. i was talking about human decency and morality and how we react to it.

the artist has a specific place in this world, and that place intersects with culture and history and their own experience in a way that is impossible to untangle. itâ€™s the place their work comes from, and itâ€™s different for everyone. and pablo picasso, who could have literally painted anything he dreamed up, spent his time among the tears he created, tears that fed his raging need, and celebrating the minotaur, the rapist, the monsters that feed their appetites no matter how vile or harmful they are.

thatâ€™s why i donâ€™t want a picasso. a couple of drawings of birds and flowers and a monumental addition to the vocabulary available to all artists forever do not redeem him.

text: i donâ€™t usually post things like this, but i will not be silent anymore. in the past few years, things have been terrible. many people have tried to take away rights of other humans, like the right to abortion, to marriage, to safety in schools and so on. this needs to stop. respect people. if someone wants an abortion, let them get one. you donâ€™t like it? donâ€™t get one. let everyone get married, donâ€™t touch a person without their consent. donâ€™t separate families.  donâ€™t judge a person based on their race or religion. everyone deserves the right to make their own choices. as a person of the lgbtq+ community, a woman, and someone who has dealt with sexual assault, i will stand up for whatâ€™s right, so others never have to go through what i, and many others have. treat people like people, donâ€™t discriminate against them because they are different from you, in religion, in gender, sexual identity, nationality, race, or anything else. if you donâ€™t like this, feel free to unfollow me, as every person deserves to have rights, and not have them taken away. #feminist #feminism #marchforourlives #equality #guncontrol #metoo #metoomovement

the last few years have taught me that actions do speak volumes and not to take someone's word as gosspil...when you love someone it's not always returned and when you think you can trust someone it's not always the case...i've learned that people i fight for wouldn't blink an eyelid if i were struggling and i've also learned that your family don't always have your back even if you have theirs...i've learned that people only speak to me when they need me and mostly i'm alone...but i'm ok with that because i know where i stand.

text: i believe it is time that i post this image once more, to drive home a point. i was going to believe i had gone through with my decrying of r. kelly publicly, and i certainly gave my piece... but it had recently become clear to me that there was a situation in my life where someone i knew, trusted and even worked together with for nearly three years was a sexual predator who tried to prey on a young black girl who for protection purposes will be left unnamed... he had begun calling her his girlfriend, when she was not of any legal age in america to be able to give consent. i will ask that none of you request information on this situation on this situation, as it is already being dealt with by the proper people in his life. however, as a survivor of sexual assault myself who was molested by a worship leader in college, in a state far from my own away from my parents, i am expressing with great and unbelievable pain the implications of potentially having saved someoneâ€™s life. it is a welcome thing that i had to do what was right, but the psychic toll of seeing yourself reflected in a situation where even your defenses were lowered makes you relive your own assault not on the level of traumatic anxiety, but of traumatic understanding and empathy. you know how when guts in berserk was struggling with ptsd from his own assault? while i donâ€™t have ptsd, itâ€™s like seeing that you rescued yourself when you couldnâ€™t have been rescued in the first place. that is why now more than ever i bring attention to mute r. kelly and the work they are doing to save these girls. please: donâ€™t let another girl end up like aaliyah. that i ever had to deal with the experience of fighting a child predator who i once called my best friend is something i cannot believe. #muterkelly #aaliyah #metoo

text:
to include this leaf in the survivor tree project is nothing short of an honor and is truly a testament to the bonds of survivorship. anne lauren of @blue_and_lavender was introduced to me by the inimitable founder of @seenheardbelieved (more on her later), and from the moment i heard her voice, i knew this woman is a force. iâ€™ve never met her in person- we spoke over the airwaves of approximately 2500 miles; but it felt as if she was sitting right next to me- opening herself up, leaning emphatically into every animated word, reassuring me that through our advocacy we will change the world. she is authentic and unabashed and it is such a privilege that i now know her even remotely. â€¢
anneâ€™s survivor story details how she had to rebuild her life after uncovering repressed sexual abuse memories at 24. these memories stretch back to the tender age of 3, involving three male members of her family. soon after, anne confronted her family and made the heartbreaking decision to walk away when they didnâ€™t believe her. she then faced the challenges stacked against survivors by the justice and healthcare systems while at the same time supporting herself through an expensive recovery process. while today she is focused on her own healing, she has made it a priority to build a network of support for fellow trauma survivors. â€œi share my story to encourage survivors and inspire them to seek healing, advocacy, safety, and justice. i think life is so beautiful and that this type of violence cannot be tolerated!â€ this incredible woman wears armor forged in pain and heartache, yet speaks and lives with such compassion and fire- iâ€™m in awe. and iâ€™m so grateful for her. check out her ig page and website link in her bio- the online survivor support community that she and her team have created is truly a gift. she is, in a word, an inspiration. from the bottom of my heart, anne- thank youâ€¦ âœ¨ðŸŒ± click the link in my bio if others would like to contribute your story to the survivor tree project. #survivor #survivoradvocate #believesurvivors #believewomen #rapesurvivor #sexualassaultsurvivor #csasurvivor #metoo #metoomovement #timesup #thesurvivortreeproject
