text:
i know that it is easier to say this quote than to actually get it done, right?! but i am sharing this with you just to remind you that there is no point of focusing on your past because it won't change what happened to you. it is a sad reality that i ended up realizing. it is a waste of time to constantly go back to your past, hoping that somehow all your bad memories will be erased. it doesn't work like this and sadly, it won't. that is the reason why we all need to focus on our future, focus on things we can actually control like our reaction through life challenges. we are the results of all the decisions and reactions we've made through life. my healing journey isn't easy at all, in my case, it is actually harder than going through the trauma itself. but still, to heal is the best decision i have ever made.

text:
no matter how slow and covert this abuse was, letâ€™s be honest: if most of us had a bit more self respect and knowingly deserving of better treatment, we wouldâ€™ve either a) set boundaries/drawn the line so much sooner and/or b) we wouldâ€™ve left. @emilyskyefit bravely posted a great video today sharing her story of her abusive ex and the terrifying things he did to her and his own family. she shared why she didnâ€™t leave sooner which included the fact that he threatened to harm her family and her dog. what stuck out most was how she went into detail about how she felt she didnâ€™t deserve love and believed she wouldnâ€™t do better. how crazy is that? victims self blame and shame ourselves enough. if we work on ourselves and love ourselves, we would never ignore so many red flags. we would recognize the mistreatment so much sooner and get out. this is so important to work on!! you do deserve love. you do deserve happiness. abuse is not your fault!

text:
i go not quietly
.
i go not quietly
i go as perfume unidentified
a shelter of pulsating pink
for those willing 
to disrobe their darkness
and make it a doormat
before stepping in
my no is not an invitation
and my wall 
is simply to manage the wolves
for my heart fills the pen
in which i stand
.
i go not quietly
i go as perfume unidentified
my delicate arms have constructed 
all of my furniture
my gentleness is gorilla glue
the tapestries off my tongue
are worth listening to
and my preciousness is pie 
only in a worthy manâ€™s sky
.
i go not quietly
i go loudly 
with a quiet truth
for i am lady
and i sing of everyoneâ€™s perfume
.
some of it youâ€™ll like
and some of it you'll not
.
.

01/09/19 at phoenix (cnn) police investigators have begun to gather dna from men who work at an arizona care facility where a woman in a vegetative state gave birth last month.

phoenix police sgt. tommy thompson said wednesday the woman and child, who was in medical distress after being delivered december 29, remain in the hospital.

cnn is not reporting the woman's name because she is the victim of sexual abuse.

cnn affiliate kpho/ktvk has reported the woman has been in a vegetative state for 14 years, quoting a source familiar with the situation. the woman has been a patient at this facility for at least a decade following a near-drowning incident when she was 15 years old, the phoenix-based station quoted its source as saying

hacienda "will accept nothing less than a full accounting of this absolutely horrifying situation, an unprecedented case that has devastated everyone involved, from the victim and her family to hacienda staff at every level of our organization," said gary orman, executive vice president of hacienda healthcare's board of directors.

last week the state's department of economic security sent investigators to the facility for health and safety checks. spokesman brett bezio said the work was finished but didn't give any details about the results of the visits with patients.

text:
#metoo 
these days all my thoughts are in my hometown of vladivostok where one brave woman katya fedorova started her fight against the wall of silence, accusing her rapist in public on her facebook page. it turned out that the rapist is a super powerful man, a co-founder a vladivostok media holding "prima-media". i do not know katya personally. i've been living away from vladivostok for quite a long time, but i still feel a strong connection with the city. i've been following the wave of bullying that has fallen on katya's shoulders these days. i do not know how she is dealing with it. vladivostok is not a very large russian city. the intellectual community is rather small and everyone knows each other - so, you can imagine what katya is risking in such a strong patriarchic society as russiaâ€™s. katya is a journalist, an activist, a founder of a feminist project "feminologi" that has given voice to women experiencing different forms of discrimination. she has helped many women and now she is herself in trouble. this is a radical notion for a local community to understand that everything a man does after a woman says "no" is violence. if you have seen the tv series "big little lies" you ought to remember janeâ€™s story, one of the main characters who experienced rape and lived in constant fear, with post-traumatic stress disorder, keeping a gun under her pillow for 7 years. what was rape in this tv show? she agreed to go to a hotel with a guy she met in a bar, she agreed on sex with him, but she did not agree to accept violence against her! how can we talk about consensual sex when a woman is traumatized, suffers bruises all over her body and is left with a broken face and in tears? why is it even an issue whether katya went with the perpetrator to a restaurant or not, whether she drank wine or not, whether she let him to walk her home or not? she was traumatized physically and mentally. that is called violence! and the bullying in social and mass media that she experiences is called victim blaming, removing once again the focus from a rapist to his victim. maybe we can start erasing some harmful patriarchal presentiments (more in comments)...

text:
can i be honest with you?

i struggle sometimes. the world of emotions and feelings have been foreign and undesirable for me. i've had a lifetime of bottling up my thoughts and opinions, experiences and emotions, and i did it out of survival. 
to survive childhood sexual abuse, i had to disconnect from myself. to survive childhood domestic abuse, i had to disconnect from myself. to survive from neglect, i had to disconnect from myself. to survive being unseen and unheard, i had to disconnect from myself. to survive my heartbreak when my mum died, i had to disconnect from myself.

do you see a theme here? by the time i got to adulthood, i didn't know how i felt. correction; i didn't feel. numbness followed by numbness.

but all the sadness, distraught, anger, upset, all the pain and disappointment i felt over the years, it didn't just disappear. it was shoved to the back or my mind and forgotten about, but it didn't forget me.

i've mentioned before about how my anxiety affects me and how depression creeps up on me every year. last year i opted to self refer to nhs counselling. i opted to take anti depressants to manage the extreme emotion i was beginning to feel.

it's like being upset but having to spend time working out why. and often it's not even current, it's feelings from the past triggered by something in the present.

i've been working on reconnecting to myself and it has been hard, it has been emotional and it has been draining. in my counselling sessions, i talk about things i've never dared to say out loud, and leave feeling a raw emotional pain in my chest, the after effect of holding back my recovery of a traumatic past; 
sexual abuse, rape, domestic violence, bereavement, emotional abuse, rape, manipulation, gaslighting, financial abuse, harassment, post natal depression, anxiety, depression.

my boundaries and self-preservation is at an all time high, but i'm sharing this because i know some of you want to reconnect with yourselves.

i want to say, yes it is hard. but you are strong. and you can do this.

we can do this.

#letshealtogether â¤
